). Second, LCO is the method solving the LCO problem in EquationÂ (
). Third, we use the state-of-the-art federated fair model training method AgnosticFair (AF)Â
As the fourth and the fifth methods in our experiments, we compare with a separate training (ST) method and the classical federated learning method FedAvgÂ
. We also extend FedAvg by two post-processing fairness enhancing methods, equalized odds (EO)Â
, to obtain the sixth and the seventh methods in our experiments.
The ST method simply asks each client
to use its own private training data set
to train a fair model by solving the following constrained optimization problem.
The post-processing methods, such as EO and CEO, are used to separately post-process the model trained by FedAvg for each client based on its private training data set. This will produce
clients. We report the average performance and the variance of those
For all the methods except AF, we use two types of models for
. One is logistic regression, the other one is a fully connected neural network with two hidden layers, where the first and the second hidden layers contain eight and four ReLU units, respectively.
We do not report the performance of AF for the neural network model because the source code of AF is not applicable to training neural networks.
